TypeScript is a typed superset of JavaScript that compiles to plain JavaScript. It is designed for the development of large applications and transcompiles to JavaScript. It adds optional static typing to the language and is intended for the development of large applications and transcompiles to JavaScript. As a superset of JavaScript, any valid JavaScript code is also valid TypeScript code. TypeScript introduces a lot of features like interfaces, classes, decorators, generics, and more. TypeScript is not a runtime, it's a compile time.

Duck Typing, on the other hand, is a prominent concept in dynamically typed languages like JavaScript. It's a principle that says that you should be able to determine the required interface from objects and just use the method and properties that exist on that object. In other words, if it walks like a duck, and it talks like a duck, then it must be a duck.

In JavaScript, this means that you don't need to know the actual type of an object, you just need to know that it has the properties and methods that you're using. This is a powerful principle because it allows for polymorphic behavior where you can write a function that works with multiple types of objects as long as they share the same interface.

To illustrate, consider the following JavaScript code:
```javascript
function quack(duck) {
  duck.makeSound();
}

let dog = {
  makeSound: function() {
    console.log('Woof Woof');
  }
};

quack(dog);
```
In this code, the `quack` function is designed to work with an object that has a `makeSound` method. Even though `dog` is not a duck, it can still quack because it has a `makeSound` method. This is the essence of duck typing.

Therefore, TypeScript and Duck Typing serve different purposes in the JavaScript ecosystem. TypeScript is a tool for better code organization and error detection at compile-time, especially in large-scale applications. Duck Typing, on the other hand, is a concept that enables you to write more reusable and flexible code by focusing on the actual interface of objects rather than their types.

To create a Discord bot with a `ban` command using Discord.js v14, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js and npm (Node Package Manager) installed on your computer. If you don't have them, download and install them from <https://nodejs.org/>.
2. Create a new folder for your bot and navigate to it in your terminal or command prompt.
3. Initialize a new Node.js application by running `npm init -y`.
4. Install Discord.js by running `npm install discord.js@14`.
5. Create an index.js file in the bot folder and add the following code:
```javascript
// index.js
const { SlashCommandHandler, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');

const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS,
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES,
  ],
});

const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Ban a user from the server.')
  .addUserOption((option) =>
    option
      .setName('user')
      .setDescription('The user to ban.')
  )
  .addStringOption((option) =>
    option
      .setName('reason')
      .setDescription('The reason for the ban.')
  );

client.slashCommands = new Map();

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  await interaction.deferReply({ ephemeral: true });

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    if (user && reason) {
      await interaction.reply({
        content: `<@!${user.id}> was banned from the server.`,
        ephemeral: true,
      });

      interaction.member
        .kick({
          days: 7,
          reason: `Banned by ${interaction.user.tag} | ${reason}`,
        })
        .catch((err) => {
          console.error(err);
          interaction.editReply({
            content: `<@!${user.id}> could not be banned due to an error.`,
            ephemeral: true,
          });
        });
    } else {
      interaction.editReply({
        content: 'You must provide a user to ban.',
        ephemeral: true,
      });
    }
  } else {
    return;
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```
Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your bot token.

1. To run the bot, execute `node index.js` in your terminal or command prompt.
2. Invite the bot to your server by navigating to <https://discord.com/oauth2/authorize?client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&scope=bot&permissions=YOUR_PERMISSIONS> (replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID` with your bot's client ID and `YOUR_PERMISSIONS` with the desired permissions).
3. The bot will now respond to the `!ban` command. When you run the command, it will ask for the user to ban and the reason for the ban.

Remember to replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID` and `YOUR_PERMISSIONS` with the appropriate values for your bot.

Here is a basic implementation of a function that converts markdown formatted text to HTML. This function only supports some basic markdown features like headers, links, images, lists, bold and italic text.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Headers
    std::regex header_regex("^#+ (.*)$");
    std::smatch match;
    if (std::regex_search(markdown, match, header_regex)) {
        html = "<h" + std::to_string(match.length() - 2) + ">" + match[1] + "</h>" + std::to_string(match.length() - 2) + ">";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }

    // Links
    std::regex link_regex("\\[([^\\[]*)\\]\\(([^\\)]*)\\)");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, link_regex)) {
        std::string text = match[1];
        std::string url = match[2];
        html += "<a href=\"" + url + "\">" + text + "</a>";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }

    // Images
    std::regex image_regex("\\!\\[(.*)\\]\\(([^\\)]*)\\)");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, image_regex)) {
        std::string alt = match[1];
        std::string url = match[2];
        html += "<img src=\"" + url + "\" alt=\"" + alt + "\">";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }

    // Lists
    std::regex list_regex("#+ (.*)");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, list_regex)) {
        std::string text = match[1];
        html += "<h1>" + text + "</h1>";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }
    std::regex list_item_regex("- +(.*)");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, list_item_regex)) {
        std::string text = match[1];
        html += "<ul><li>" + text + "</li></ul>";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }

    // Bold and Italic
    std::regex bold_regex("\\*\\*(.+?)\\*\\*");
    std::regex italic_regex("\\* (.+?) \\*");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, bold_regex)) {
        std::string text = match[1];
        html += "<strong>" + text + "</strong>";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, italic_regex)) {
        std::string text = match[1];
        html += "<em>" + text + "</em>";
        markdown = markdown.substr(match.length());
    }

    // Any remaining markdown text is converted to HTML plain text
    html += markdown;

    return html;
}
```

This function uses regular expressions to match and replace markdown patterns with their corresponding HTML. The regular expressions used here are very basic, and may not match all valid markdown patterns. You may need to modify or extend these regular expressions to suit your needs.

Please note that this function does not handle all markdown features. For example, it does not support code blocks, tables, or certain types of links and images. It also does not correctly handle markdown inside HTML tags. For a complete markdown to HTML conversion, you might want to consider using an existing library like pandoc or showdown.

