The `==` operator checks if the two compared objects are exactly the same object in memory. It does not compare the actual contents of the strings. This means that if you have two different string objects with the same content, `==` will return `false`.

On the other hand, the `equals()` method compares the contents of the strings. It checks if the characters in the two strings are the same, regardless of whether they are stored in the same object in memory. This means that if you have two string objects with the same content, `equals()` will return `true`.

Here's an example:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
